00:03:02.306 --> 00:03:09.724
If we want this expression to truly be the same expression as the product of these two things,

00:03:09.724 --> 00:03:12.207
we have to constrain its domain.

00:03:12.207 --> 00:03:15.156
We have to constrain the variable values here.

00:03:15.156 --> 00:03:17.391
Because this expression right over here.

00:03:17.391 --> 00:03:19.474
This is defined for any a's or x's.

00:03:19.474 --> 00:03:22.706
You could put any a or x here, and you will get a value here.

00:03:22.706 --> 00:03:26.958
But this product over here, this was not defined for any a's or x's.

00:03:26.958 --> 00:03:30.508
The b's cancel out, but it was not defined for any a's or x's.

00:03:30.508 --> 00:03:38.842
In this situation, if either a or x equal to 0, this expression right over here would be undefined.

00:03:38.842 --> 00:03:42.453
In fact if b was equal to 0, this expression would also be undefined.

00:03:42.453 --> 00:03:46.404
So if you really this to be the exact same expression.

00:03:46.404 --> 00:03:48.088
Say this was a function definition.

00:03:48.088 --> 00:03:54.537
If you want it to be the exact same function definition as this over here, you would have to have the same domain.

00:03:54.537 --> 00:03:56.203
So I'll just write down the domain here.

00:03:56.203 --> 00:03:57.590
They have to have the same domain.

00:03:57.590 --> 00:03:59.195
If you want them to be the exact same function.

00:03:59.195 --> 00:04:02.362
If you don't care about that, then you could just say, ok let's just go with this.

00:04:02.362 --> 00:04:07.203
But you should constrain it if you want it to be an equivalent expression.

00:04:07.203 --> 00:04:16.686
And so in either case, you should constrain the domain to be all real numbers.

00:04:16.686 --> 00:04:17.757
And this is a bit different, because

00:04:17.757 --> 00:04:20.659
